{"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **Dealing with nonlinear relationships using random forests**\n","\n","A random forest is an ensemble of multiple **decision trees**. Unlike global linear and polynomial regression models, decision trees subdivide the input space into smaller, manageable regions, functioning as the sum of piecewise linear functions."],"metadata":{"id":"gkwbCxm6XFNc"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import pandas as pd\n","\n","# Define the subset of columns to use\n","columns = ['Overall Qual', 'Overall Cond', 'Gr Liv Area',\n","           'Central Air', 'Total Bsmt SF', 'SalePrice']\n","\n","# Load the dataset\n","df = pd.read_csv('http://jse.amstat.org/v19n3/decock/AmesHousing.txt',\n","                 sep='\\t',\n","                 usecols=columns)\n","\n","# Map string categorical variables to integers\n","df['Central Air'] = df['Central Air'].map({'N': 0, 'Y': 1})\n","\n","# Drop rows containing missing values (Total Bsmt SF has 1 missing value)\n","df = df.dropna(axis=0)"],"metadata":{"id":"-sZit2WXX0_3","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781965789500,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":357,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}}},"execution_count":23,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","\n","def lin_regplot(X, y, model):\n","    plt.scatter(X, y, c='steelblue', edgecolor='white', s=70)\n","    plt.plot(X, model.predict(X), color='black', lw=2)\n","    return"],"metadata":{"id":"P3yKxjQTYfad","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781965789515,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":2,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}}},"execution_count":24,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## **Decision Tree Regression**\n","\n","An advantage of decision trees is that they work with arbitrary features without requiring transformation, normalization, or standardization for nonlinear data.\n","\n","### **Splitting Criteria**\n","\n","In classification, decision trees split nodes to maximize **Information Gain (IG)**:\n","\n","$$IG(D_p, x_i) = I(D_p) - \\frac{N_{left}}{N_p}I(D_{left}) - \\frac{N_{right}}{N_p}I(D_{right})$$\n","\n","For regression, however, we use an impurity metric suitable for continuous variables, defining the impurity measure of a node $t$ as the **Mean Squared Error (MSE)** (often referred to as within-node variance or variance reduction):\n","\n","$$I(t) = MSE(t) = \\frac{1}{N_t} \\sum_{i \\in D_t} (y^{(i)} - \\hat{y}_t)^2$$\n","\n","Where the predicted target value (sample mean) is:\n","\n","$$\\hat{y}_t = \\frac{1}{N_t} \\sum_{i \\in D_t} y^{(i)}$$"],"metadata":{"id":"iVZgNZyXWopj"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **Code: Fitting a Decision Tree Regressor**"],"metadata":{"id":"c4RvK6GQXcQu"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor\n","\n","X = df[['Gr Liv Area']].values\n","y = df['SalePrice'].values\n","\n","tree = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=3)\n","tree.fit(X, y)\n","\n","sort_idx = X.flatten().argsort()\n","lin_regplot(X[sort_idx], y[sort_idx], tree)\n","plt.xlabel('Living area above ground in square feet')\n","plt.ylabel('Sale price in U.S. dollars')\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":25,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":449},"id":"OGlg1oGaWopm","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781965789681,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":167,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"e78ccc4e-af3f-41f9-cbc8-ac7f72fb3494"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor\n","\n","X = df[['Overall Qual']].values\n","y = df['SalePrice'].values\n","\n","tree = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth=3)\n","tree.fit(X, y)\n","\n","sort_idx = X.flatten().argsort()\n","lin_regplot(X[sort_idx], y[sort_idx], tree)\n","plt.xlabel('Living area above ground in square feet')\n","plt.ylabel('Sale price in U.S. dollars')\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":449},"id":"9aSAUpMmY0Hm","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781965789843,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":161,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"f52453cc-5cc0-4b6a-830a-266bc034cf58"},"execution_count":26,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["*(Note: A limitation of standard regression trees is that they do not capture the continuity and differentiability of the desired prediction, looking like stepped lines rather than smooth curves.)*\n","\n","---"],"metadata":{"id":"4Zkez3P4Wopo"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## **Random Forest Regression**\n","\n","A random forest combines multiple decision trees to decrease the model's variance, resulting in better generalization performance. They are less sensitive to outliers and require minimal parameter tuning (mostly just adjusting the number of trees). The predicted target variable is calculated as the average prediction across all decision trees."],"metadata":{"id":"ubgMYpTAZB0A"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **Code: Fitting and Evaluating a Random Forest Regressor**"],"metadata":{"id":"ZYRwN2C6ZDlY"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split\n","from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor\n","from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, r2_score\n","\n","target = 'SalePrice'\n","features = df.columns[df.columns != target]\n","X = df[features].values\n","y = df[target].values\n","\n","X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(\n","    X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=123)\n","\n","forest = RandomForestRegressor(\n","    n_estimators=1000,\n","    criterion='squared_error',\n","    random_state=1,\n","    n_jobs=-1)\n","\n","forest.fit(X_train, y_train)\n","\n","y_train_pred = forest.predict(X_train)\n","y_test_pred = forest.predict(X_test)\n","\n","mae_train = mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_train_pred)\n","mae_test = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_test_pred)\n","print(f'MAE train: {mae_train:.2f}')\n","print(f'MAE test: {mae_test:.2f}')\n","\n","r2_train = r2_score(y_train, y_train_pred)\n","r2_test = r2_score(y_test, y_test_pred)\n","print(f'R^2 train: {r2_train:.2f}')\n","print(f'R^2 test: {r2_test:.2f}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["MAE train: 8305.18\n","MAE test: 20821.77\n","R^2 train: 0.98\n","R^2 test: 0.85\n"]}],"execution_count":27,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"Vbn8rYGCWopp","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781965797736,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":7892,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"e2b60c35-ac25-4985-8365-1c9659aa129a"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["---\n","\n","## **Analyzing Residuals**\n","\n","Analyzing the residuals helps determine if the model captures the exploratory information correctly. Ideally, model errors should be random. If residual plots show patterns, it indicates predictive information is leaking into the errors.\n","\n","### **Code: Plotting Residuals**"],"metadata":{"id":"3vEvjROzWopp"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["import numpy as np\n","\n","x_max = np.max([np.max(y_train_pred), np.max(y_test_pred)])\n","x_min = np.min([np.min(y_train_pred), np.min(y_test_pred)])\n","\n","fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(7, 3), sharey=True)\n","\n","ax1.scatter(y_test_pred, y_test_pred - y_test,\n","            c='limegreen', marker='s', edgecolor='white',\n","            label='Test data')\n","\n","ax2.scatter(y_train_pred, y_train_pred - y_train,\n","            c='steelblue', marker='o', edgecolor='white',\n","            label='Training data')\n","\n","ax1.set_ylabel('Residuals')\n","\n","for ax in (ax1, ax2):\n","    ax.set_xlabel('Predicted values')\n","    ax.legend(loc='upper left')\n","    ax.hlines(y=0, xmin=x_min-100, xmax=x_max+100, color='black', lw=2)\n","\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 700x300 with 2 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":28,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":307},"id":"22TcVPWLWopp","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781965798078,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":345,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"a8db0eaa-a6b8-41f9-c594-00fbadbfd241"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### **Handling Non-Random Residuals**\n","\n","There is no universal fix for non-randomness in residual plots. It requires experimentation, such as:\n","\n","* Transforming variables\n","* Tuning hyperparameters\n","* Choosing simpler or more complex models\n","* Removing outliers\n","* Including additional variables"],"metadata":{"id":"xWC-Of0QWopq"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"vJV9_PwZaN4e","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781965798101,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":4,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}}},"execution_count":28,"outputs":[]}],"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}